photo.description: The Gateway Arch, or Gateway to the West,[5] is an arch that is the centerpiece of the Jefferson National Expansion Memorial in St. Louis, Missouri. It was built as a monument to the westward expansion of the United States. At 630 feet (192 m), it is the tallest man-made monument in the United States,[4] Missouri's tallest accessible building, and the largest architectural structure designed as a weighted or flattened catenary arch.[4] The arch is located at the site of St. Louis' foundation,[6] on the west bank of the Mississippi River where Pierre Laclède, just after noon on February 14, 1764, told his aide, Auguste Chouteau, to build a city. Source:http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gateway_Arch Edit.

photo.description: The Arch commemorates St Louis' role as the gateway to western migration. It is 630 feet high and 630feet wide at the base. The site was cleared in 1933 and a national design competition was held for the memorial in 1948 and won by Eero Saarinen. construction began in 1963 and was completed in 1965. An underground museum and visitor centre is situated under the arch.
